The relationship between salary, gender, and national GDP.#

Author: Kailin Wu (kailiw1@uci.edu)

Course Project, UC Irvine, Math 10, Summer 2023

Introduction#

In this study, I analyze a dataset containing economic indicators from multiple countries, highlighting key parameters such as GDP, GDP per capita, gender-based wage differences, and median incomes. The main goal is to clarify the complex relationship between individual earnings, gender dynamics, and a nationâ€™s GDP. To achieve this, I compared various machine learning algorithms to determine their predictive capabilities and then presented the results through user-friendly visualizations. Throughout this analysis, we will use tools such as pandas, Altair Chart, and logistic regression to decipher the complex connections among economic metrics objectively.

Gender Gap#

People often wonder, does gender truly impact oneâ€™s salary? Here, we will discuss the wage (hourly wage) differences between men and women in the selected six countries. Do male hourly wages differ from female hourly wages?

import altair as alt

# cm: chart for male
# cf: chart for female

cm = alt.Chart(df_pay[df_pay['gender'] == 'Male']).mark_line().encode(
    x='year:O',
    y='amount_local_currency:Q',
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'year', 'amount_local_currency']
).properties(
    title='Amount in Local Currency by Year for Male')

cf = alt.Chart(df_pay[df_pay['gender'] == 'Female']).mark_line().encode(
    x='year:O',
    y=alt.Y('amount_local_currency:Q', scale=alt.Scale(domain=[0, 90])),
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'year', 'amount_local_currency']
).properties(
    title='Amount in Local Currency by Year for Female')

cf | cm

The chart on the left represents â€œAmount in Local Currency by Year for Female,â€ while the one on the right is for Males, and both charts have consistent y-axis scales. At a glance, it seems that the salary levels for females in the six countries discussed are lower than those for males. However, the comparison is not very intuitive. Below, we will break it down into six charts by country to compare the (hourly) wages of men and women.

c6_pay = alt.Chart(df_pay[df_pay['gender'].isin(['Female', 'Male'])]
).mark_line().encode(

c6_pay

Based on the chart â€œSalary by Gender over Years,â€ we can clearly see that there is a significant gender pay gap in all six countries, as indicated by the blue line is lower than the orange line (where the orange line represents male salaries and the blue line represents female salaries). Among them, Switzerland has the largest gender pay gap, while Moldova and Portugal have moments where the male and female salaries are very close (with the two data points almost overlapping). To better compare the size of the gender pay gap, we will create a chart based on the â€˜gender gapâ€™ (i.e., male salary minus female salary).

# make a DataFrame that only have 'Gender gap' as gender
# then calculate the average of 'Gender gap'

df_gap = df_pay[df_pay['gender'] == 'Gender gap']
df_gap = df_gap[['country', 'gender', 'amount_local_currency', 'year']]

df_gap = df_gap.groupby('country')['amount_local_currency'].mean().reset_index()
df_gap.columns = ['country', 'average_gender_gap']

c_gap = alt.Chart(df_pay[df_pay['gender'] == 'Gender gap']).mark_line().encode(
    x='year:O',
    y='amount_local_currency:Q',
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'year', 'amount_local_currency']
).properties(
    title='Gender Gap by Year')

b_gap = alt.Chart(df_gap).mark_bar().encode(
    x='country:N',
    y='average_gender_gap:Q',
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'average_gender_gap']
).properties(
    title='Average Gender Gap by Country')

c_gap | b_gap

Through the bar graph â€œAverage Gender Gap by Country,â€ we can clearly see the countries ranked from highest to lowest: Switzerland, the United States, Spain, Moldova, France, and Portugal. Additionally, based on the line chart â€œGender Gap by Yearâ€, we can observe that the smallest gender pay gap occurred in Portugal in 2017, while the largest was in Switzerland in 2015.

GDP and GDP per capita#

GDP offers a broad view of a nationâ€™s economic activity, reflecting its financial stability and growth. It serves as a tool to gauge and compare the economic prowess of various countries.

GDP per capita is the GDP of a country divided by its population. This metric provides insights into the average economic prosperity and quality of life for individuals in a nation.

A country might have a high GDP but a low GDP per capita, indicating that while the country as a whole is wealthy, its residents, on average, might not be (and vice versa). Therefore, in this context, I need to analyze both GDP and GDP per capita in order to prepare for subsequent research that explores whether thereâ€™s a relationship between a countryâ€™s economic status and its wage standards, as well as the degree of gender wage inequality.

# GDP
# converting the data from wide to long format
# creat a column with GDP in billion $

df_g2 = df_gdp.melt(id_vars=['country'], var_name='year', value_name='GDP')
df_g2['GDP_billion'] = df_g2['GDP'] / 1000000000

# GDP per capita
# converting the data from wide to long format
# creat a column with GDP in thousand $

df_p = df_gdp_pp.melt(id_vars=['country'], var_name='year', value_name='GDP_per_capita')
df_p['GDP_thousand'] = df_p['GDP_per_capita'] / 1000

# combime the 2 DataFrame
df_g2 = pd.merge(df_g2, df_p, on=['country', 'year'])

c_gdp = alt.Chart(df_g2).mark_line().encode(
    x='year:O',
    y='GDP_billion:Q',
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'year', 'GDP']
).properties(
    title='GDP',
    width=300,
    height=300)

c_pp = alt.Chart(df_p).mark_line().encode(
    x='year:O',
    y='GDP_thousand:Q',
    color='country:N',
    tooltip=['country', 'year', 'GDP_per_capita']
).properties(
    title='GDP per capita',
    width=300,
    height=300)

c_gdp | c_pp

The configuration of the Altair charts above was adapted from â€œthis link.â€

I didnâ€™t notice a strong relationship between GDP and GDP per capita from the two charts above. Countries with a high GDP donâ€™t necessarily have a high GDP per capita. Take the United States as an example: its total GDP far surpasses the other five countries, yet its GDP per capita is lower than Switzerlandâ€™s. Meanwhile, Switzerland ranks only fourth in GDP among the six countries (third from the bottom) but consistently ranks first in GDP per capita.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

For each country, the higher the GDP, the higher the GDP per capita, showing a linear relationship. However, the conversion ratio between these two data points is inconsistent across countries, in which the slope of the linear relationship varies for each country.

Since most red crosses are close to the blue points, it suggests the model has a good predictive performance on the test set. There is one outlier (a point that is far away from the general cluster of data points), which might influence the modelâ€™s predictions, but I couldnâ€™t tell why it exists.

Summary#

The analysis examines the complex relationships between GDP, GDP per capita, gender, and salary in six countries: Switzerland, Spain, France, Moldova, Portugal, and the United States. Initial visualizations suggest that while countries with higher GDP donâ€™t necessarily have higher GDP per capita, there is a discernible gender pay gap in all countries. The study also uses Logistic Regression classifiers to further understand some of these relationships, but the correlation between different factors remains nuanced and not always linear.
